2026-04-16 12:16:20 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['power supply module – internal series path from battery to output terminals'] hypothesis_explanation='Given the constraints: (1) the PSU green LED is ON, proving the battery and at least some internal wiring and LED branch are powered; (2) all eight control‑module switches are confirmed closed, so their series contacts are not open; (3) all inter‑module cabling is correctly polarized with no observed swaps; (4) the load module (lamp, indicator lamp, and diode) is present with no visible damage, and we could not demonstrate an internal open there; and (5) all control‑module indicator branches have been removed but these were always wired as shunt branches and cannot break the main series line, the only remaining element uniquely consistent with “PSU LED on but no voltage reaching any downstream module and lamp dark” is an internal open circuit in the PSU’s main output path.\n\nThe most plausible root cause is that the power‑supply module’s battery output is no longer connected (or only intermittently/not at all connected) to its outgoing + and/or − terminals, even though the LED branch inside that module still has a local return path to the battery. This could be due to a broken trace, failed connector, or internal mis‑wiring that isolates the external output from the source while leaving the LED circuit intact. Replacing/repairing the PSU module’s main series path from the battery to the output terminals should restore power to the rest of the chain and allow the downstream lamp to operate when all switches are ON.'
